WRITING.TITLE: b' '
WRITING.TEXT:
b'You are right, but there is a bit more to it. The ticket costs 10 euros (which is already cheaper than most combined tickets), and you are expected to use it at least 16 times up until December 31th. If you do, then you can ask back those 10 euros. If not, you simply lose them. Pretty good deal if you ask me. 

You also have the option of a "mid-distance train" ticket, which uses a different type of train that reaches even further, and that could be interesting in your case. The only difference is that this one costs 20 euros, the other conditions remain the same.

Now that I think about it, you need to use your dni to get the ticket. I suppose you can introduce your nie and it should work just fine, tho.'

WRITING.TEXT:
b"Depends on many factors. If you are going to live alone, expect at least 700~800\xe2\x82\xac on rent. If you are going to share a flat, ~400 \xe2\x82\xac should do the trick. I'm talking about Barcelona, but you would find similar prices even in nearby towns or cities.

 Then, for other expenses, electricity, water, etc, those are expensive nowadays, so put another 200-250 euros (once again, divide by the number of people if you share). Groceries, if you prepare everything yourself, around 150~200\xe2\x82\xac a month should be plenty. If you like eating on a resturant or asking food delivery, that number skyrockets. Lastly, take into account that transport, if you use it often, would be around 50\xe2\x82\xac a month. 

With all of that, you should have a better idea of your budget. Barcelona is great, but kind of expensive, and it shows no sign of stopping soon."
